# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abbreviation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abbreviation/1933-in-germany] The pivotal nature of **1933 in Germany** has led to it being a commonly used analogy in modern politics.
[src:abbreviation/1933-in-germany] The 1933 power grab by the Nazi party has been associated with modern political events, particularly the Presidency of Donald Trump in the United States and the 2023 Israeli judicial reform (eventually passed in 2025).
[src:abbreviation/1933-in-germany] Israeli journalists and others repeated or elaborated on Blatman's compassion.
[src:abbreviation/1933-in-germany] In a 2017 essay titled "The Reichstag Fire Next Time: The coming crackdown" Russian-American journalist M.
[src:abbreviation/1933-in-germany] Gessen wrote, "The Reichstag fire, it goes almost without saying, will be a terrorist attack, and it will mark our sudden, obvious, and irreversible descent into autocracy".
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] The work is often referred to as "Turabian" (after the work's original author, Kate L.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] Turabian) or by the shortened title, *A Manual for Writers*.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] The style and formatting of academic works, described within the manual, is commonly referred to as "Turabian style" or "Chicago style" (being based on that of *The Chicago Manual of Style*).
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] The ninth edition of the manual, published in 2018, corresponds with the 17th edition of *The Chicago Manual of Style*.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] Except for a few minor differences, the style and formatting described in the ninth edition of the manual is the same as the 17th edition of *The Chicago Manual of Style*.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] Part 1 of the manual approaches the process of research and writing.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] This includes providing "practical advice" to formulate "the right questions, read critically, and build arguments" as well as helping authors draft and revise a paper.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] Initially added with the seventh edition of the manual, this part is adapted from *The Craft of Research*.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] Part 2 of the manual explores the two methods of citing/documenting sources used in authoring a work: (1) the notes-bibliography style; and (2) the author-date style.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] The more-concise author-date style (sometimes referred to as the "reference list style") is more common in the physical, natural, and social sciences.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] The manual provides extensive examples of how to cite different types of works (e.g. books, journal articles, websites, etc.) using both citation styles.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] Part 3 of the manual "addresses matters of spelling, punctuation, abbreviation, and treatment of numbers, names, special terms, and titles of works." This part also provides guidance on including quotations from different sources as well as the formatting of tables and figures.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] The appendix provides specific requirements on the formatting of research papers as well as theses and dissertations.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] General formatting requirements include recommendations on paper and margin sizes, options as to the choice of typeface, the spacing and indentation of text, pagination, and the use of titles.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] Formatting requirements for specific elements include the ordering and formatting of content in the front matter, main matter (text), and back matter of a work.
[src:abbreviation/a-manual-for-writers-of-research-papers-theses-and-dissertations] The appendix also includes a description on preparing and submitting files, both electronically and as hard copies.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] The continued repetition of a note or chord is expressed by a stroke or strokes across the stem, or above or below the note if it be a whole note or double whole note.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] The number of strokes denotes the subdivision of the written note into eighth notes, sixteenth notes, etc., unless the word tremolo or tremolando is added, in which case the repetition is as rapid as possible, without regard to the exact number of notes played.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] (When strokes are added to notes shorter than a quarter note, each beam counts as a stroke.) In the first bar of the example below, the half note with the single stroke across the stem in the *written* staff becomes 4 eighth notes in the *played* staff.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] Through the use of 2 strokes across the stem in the second bar, the next full note is expressed as a phrase of 16 sixteenth notes.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] On bowed instruments the rapid reiteration of a single note is easy, but in piano music an octave or chord becomes necessary to produce a tremolo, the manner of writing and performing of which is seen below.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] In the abbreviation expressed by strokes, as above, the passage to be abbreviated can contain no note of greater length than an eighth note, but it is possible also to divide a long note into quarter notes, by means of dots (sometimes known as *divisi* dots) placed over it, as below.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] This is however seldom done, as only a small amount of space is saved.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] When a long note has to be repeated in the form of triplets or sextuplets, the figure 3 or 6 is usually placed over it in addition to the stroke across the stem, and the note is sometimes, though not necessarily, written dotted.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] The repetition of a group of two notes is abbreviated by two notes (most often half notes or whole notes) connected by the number of strokes ordinarily used to express eighth notes, sixteenth notes, etc., according to the rate of movement intended, as below.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] It will be observed that a passage lasting for the value of one half note requires two half notes to express it, on account of the group consisting of two notes.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] A group of three, four, or more notes is abbreviated by the repetition of the cross strokes without the notes as many times as the group has to be repeated.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] This can also be written with the notes forming the group are written as a chord, with the necessary number of strokes across the stem.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] In this case the word *simili* or *segue* is added, to show that the order of notes in the first group (which must be written out in full) is to be repeated, and to prevent the possibility of mistaking the effect intended for the repetition of the chord as a whole.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] Another sign of abbreviation of a group consists of an oblique line with two dots, one on each side; this serves to indicate the repetition of a group of any number of notes of any length.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] This can even apply to a passage composed of several groups, provided such passage is not more than two bars in length.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] A more usual method of abbreviating the repetition of a passage of the length of the above is to write over it the word *bis* (twice), or in some cases *ter* (three times), or to enclose it between the dots of an ordinary repeat sign.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] Passages intended to be played in octaves are often written as single notes with the words *coll' ottava* or *coll' 8va* placed above or below them, according as the upper or lower octave is to be added.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] The word *8va* (or sometimes *8va alta* or *8va bassa*) written above or below a passage does not add octaves, but merely transposes the passage an octave higher or lower.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] In clarinet music the word *chalumeau* is used to signify that the passage is to be played an octave lower than written.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] All these alterations (which can scarcely be considered abbreviations except that they spare the use of ledger lines) are counteracted, and the passage restored to its usual position, by the ending of the enclosing bracket, the word *loco*, or in clarinet music *clarinette*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] Where two parts are written on one staff in a score the sign *a 2* denotes that both play the same notes; and *a 1* that the second of the two is resting.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] The indication *a 3* or *a 4* at the head of fugues indicates the number of parts or voices in which the fugue is written.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] An abbreviation which is often very troublesome to the conductor occurs in manuscript scores, when a considerable part of the composition is repeated without alteration, and the corresponding number of bars are left vacant, with the remark *come sopra* (as above).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] There are also abbreviations relating to music analysis, some of which are of great value.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] In figured bass, for instance, the various chords are expressed by figures, and the several authors in the nineteenth century invented or availed themselves of various methods of shortly expressing the different chords and intervals, particularly using Roman numeral analysis.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation-music] Gottfried Weber represents an interval by a number with one or two dots before it to express minor or diminished, and one or two after it for major or augmented.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] An **abbreviation** (from Latin **brevis** 'short') is a shortened form of a word or phrase, by any method including shortening, contraction, initialism (which includes acronym), or crasis.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] An abbreviation may be a shortened form of a word, usually ended with a trailing full stop (period).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For example, the term *etc.* is the usual abbreviation for the Latin phrase *et cetera*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] A *contraction* is an abbreviation formed by leaving out letters or sounds, typically replaced by an apostrophe in English.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Examples include *I'm* for *I am* and *li'l* for *little*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] An *initialism* or *acronym* is an abbreviation consisting of the initial letter of a sequence of words without other punctuation.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For example, FBI (/ˌɛf.biːˈaɪ/), USA (/ˌjuː.ɛsˈeɪ/), IBM (/ˌaɪ.biːˈɛm/), BBC (/ˌbiː.biːˈsiː/).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] When initialism is used as the preferred term, acronym refers more specifically to when the abbreviation is pronounced as a word rather than as separate letters; examples include SWAT and NASA.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Initialisms, contractions and crasis share some semantic and phonetic functions, and are connected by the term *abbreviation* in loose parlance.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In early times, abbreviations may have been common due to the effort involved in writing (many inscriptions were carved in stone) or to provide secrecy via obfuscation.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Reduction of a word to a single letter was common in both Greek and Roman writing.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In Roman inscriptions, "Words were commonly abbreviated by using the initial letter or letters of words, and most inscriptions have at least one abbreviation".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] However, "some could have more than one meaning, depending on their context.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Abbreviations were frequently used in early English.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Manuscripts of copies of the Old English poem *Beowulf* used many abbreviations, for example the Tironian et (⁊) or & for *and*, and y for *since*, so that "not much space is wasted".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The standardisation of English in the 15th through 17th centuries included a growth in the use of such abbreviations.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] At first, abbreviations were sometimes represented with various suspension signs, not only periods.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For example, sequences like ⟨er⟩ were replaced with ⟨ɔ⟩, as in mastɔ for *master* and exacɔbate for *exacerbate*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] While this may seem trivial, it was symptomatic of an attempt by people manually reproducing academic texts to reduce the copy time.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] — Warden of Merton College, University of Oxford in *Registrum Annalium Collegii Mertonensis*, 1503.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In the Early Modern English period, between the 15th and 17th centuries, the thorn Þ was used for *th*, as in Þe ('the').
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In modern times, ⟨Þ⟩ was often used (in the form ⟨y⟩) for promotional reasons, as in Ye Olde Tea Shoppe.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] During the growth of philological linguistic theory in academic Britain, abbreviating became very fashionable.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Likewise, a century earlier in Boston, a fad of abbreviation started that swept the United States, with the globally popular term OK generally credited as a remnant of its influence.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Over the years, however, the lack of convention in some style guides has made it difficult to determine which two-word abbreviations should be abbreviated with periods and which should not.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Widespread use of electronic communication through mobile phones and the Internet during the 1990s led to a marked rise in colloquial abbreviation.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] This was due largely to increasing popularity of textual communication services such as instant and text messaging.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The original SMS supported message lengths of 160 characters at most (using the GSM 03.38 character set), for instance.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] This brevity gave rise to an informal abbreviation scheme sometimes called Textese, with which 10% or more of the words in a typical SMS message are abbreviated.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] More recently Twitter, a popular social networking service, began driving abbreviation use with 140 character message limits.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In HTML, abbreviations can be annotated using a dedicated tag: `<abbr title="Editor">Ed.</abbr>` In this example, the meaning of "Ed." as "Editor" is revealed by hovering the cursor over it.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In modern English, there are multiple conventions for abbreviation, and there is controversy as to which should be used.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] One generally accepted rule is to be consistent in a body of work.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] To this end, publishers may express their preferences in a style guide.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Some controversies that arise are described below.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] If the original word was capitalized then the first letter of its abbreviation should retain the capital, for example Lev. for *Leviticus*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] When a word is abbreviated to more than a single letter and was originally spelled with lower case letters then there is no need for capitalization.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] However, when abbreviating a phrase where only the first letter of each word is taken, then all letters should be capitalized, as in YTD for *year-to-date*, PCB for *printed circuit board* and FYI for *for your information*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] However, see the following section regarding abbreviations that have become common vocabulary: these are no longer written with capital letters.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] A period (full stop) is sometimes used to signify abbreviation, but opinion is divided as to when and if this convention is best practice.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] According to Hart's Rules, a word shortened by dropping letters from the end terminates with a full stop (period), whereas a word shorted by dropping letters from the middle does not.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Fowler's Modern English Usage says a full stop (period) is used for both of these shortened forms, but recommends against this practice.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] It advises it only for end-shortened words and lower-case initialisms, not for middle-shortened words and upper-case initialisms.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Some British style guides, such as for The Guardian and The Economist, disallow periods for all abbreviations.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In American English, the period is usually included regardless of whether or not it is a contraction, e.g.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] *Dr.* or *Mrs.* In some cases, periods are optional, as in either *US* or *U.S.* for *United States*, *EU* or *E.U.* for *European Union*, and *UN* or *U.N.* for *United Nations*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] There are some house styles, however—American ones included—that remove the periods from almost all abbreviations.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Acronyms that were originally capitalized (with or without periods) but have since entered the vocabulary as generic words are no longer written with capital letters nor with any periods.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Examples are sonar, radar, lidar, laser, snafu, and scuba.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In the past, some initialisms were styled with a period after each letter and a space between each pair.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] There are multiple ways to pluralize an abbreviation.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Sometimes this accomplished by adding an apostrophe and an *s* ('s), as in "two PC's have broken screens".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] But, some find this confusing since the notation can indicate possessive case.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] And, this style is deprecated by many style guides.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For instance, Kate Turabian, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For example, "DVDs" and "URLs" and "Ph.D.'s", while the Modern Language Association explicitly says, "do not use an apostrophe to form the plural of an abbreviation".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Also, the American Psychological Association specifically says, "without an apostrophe".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] However, the 1999 style guide for *The New York Times* states that the addition of an apostrophe is necessary when pluralizing all abbreviations, preferring "PC's, TV's and VCR's".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Forming a plural of an initialization without an apostrophe can also be used for a number, or a letter.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For units of measure, the same form is used for both singular and plural.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] When an abbreviation contains more than one period, *Hart's Rules* recommends putting the *s* after the final one.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] According to *Hart's Rules*, an apostrophe may be used in rare cases where clarity calls for it, for example when letters or symbols are referred to as objects.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In Latin, and continuing to the derivative forms in European languages as well as English, single-letter abbreviations had the plural being a doubling of the letter for note-taking.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Most of these deal with writing and publishing.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] A few longer abbreviations use this as well.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Publications based in the U.S. tend to follow the style guides of *The Chicago Manual of Style* and the Associated Press.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The U.S. government follows a style guide published by the U.S.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The National Institute of Standards and Technology sets the style for abbreviations of units.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Writers often use shorthand to denote units of measure.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Such shorthand can be an abbreviation, such as "in" for "inch" or can be a symbol such as "km" for "kilometre".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In the International System of Units (SI) manual the word "symbol" is used consistently to define the shorthand used to represent the various SI units of measure.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] A syllabic abbreviation is usually formed from the initial syllables of several words, such as *Interpol* = *International* + *police*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are usually written using lower case, sometimes starting with a capital letter, and are always pronounced as words rather than letter by letter.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations should be distinguished from portmanteaus, which combine two words without necessarily taking whole syllables from each.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not widely used in English.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Some UK government agencies such as Ofcom (Office of Communications) and the former Oftel (Office of Telecommunications) use this style.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] New York City has various neighborhoods named by syllabic abbreviation, such as Tribeca (Triangle below Canal Street) and SoHo (South of Houston Street).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] This usage has spread into other American cities, giving SoMa, San Francisco (South of Market), and LoDo, Denver (Lower Downtown), amongst others.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Sections of California are also often colloquially syllabically abbreviated, as in NorCal (Northern California), CenCal (Central California), and SoCal (Southern California).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Additionally, in the context of Los Angeles, the syllabic abbreviation SoHo (Southern Hollywood) refers to the southern portion of the Hollywood neighborhood.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Partially syllabic abbreviations are preferred by the US Navy, as they increase readability amidst the large number of initialisms that would otherwise have to fit into the same acronyms.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Hence *DESRON 6* is used (in the full capital form) to mean "Destroyer Squadron 6", while *COMNAVAIRLANT* would be "Commander, Naval Air Force (in the) Atlantic".
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are a prominent feature of Newspeak, the fictional language of George Orwell's dystopian novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The political contractions of Newspeak—*Ingsoc* (English Socialism), *Minitrue* (Ministry of Truth), *Miniplenty* (Ministry of Plenty)—are described by Orwell as similar to real examples of German *(see below)* and Russian (*see below)* contractions in the 20th century.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The contractions in Newspeak are supposed to have a political function by virtue of their abbreviated structure itself: nice sounding and easily pronounceable, their purpose is to mask all ideological content from the speaker.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] A more recent syllabic abbreviation has emerged with the disease COVID-19 (Corona Virus Disease 2019) caused by the Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 (itself frequently abbreviated to SARS-CoV-2, partly an initialism).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In Albanian, syllabic acronyms are sometimes used for composing a person's name, such as *Migjeni*—an abbreviation from his original name (*Millosh Gjergj Nikolla*) a famous Albanian poet and writer—or *ASDRENI* (*Aleksander Stavre Drenova*), another famous Albanian poet.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Other such names which are used commonly in recent decades are GETOAR, composed from *Gegeria* + *Tosks* (representing the two main dialects of the Albanian language, Gegë and Toskë), and *Arbanon*—which is an alternative way used to describe all Albanian lands.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations were and are common in German; much like acronyms in English, they have a distinctly modern connotation, although contrary to popular belief, many date back to before 1933, if not the end of the Great War.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] *Kriminalpolizei*, literally *criminal police* but idiomatically the Criminal Investigation Department of any German police force, begat *KriPo* (variously capitalised), and likewise *Schutzpolizei* (*protection police* or *uniform department*) begat *SchuPo*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Along the same lines, the Swiss Federal Railways' Transit Police—the *Transportpolizei*—are abbreviated as the *TraPo*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] With the National Socialist German Workers' Party gaining power came a frenzy of government reorganisation, and with it a series of entirely new syllabic abbreviations.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Non regime-aligned partially syllabic abbreviations also existed like "Gröfaz" for the self-proclaimed "größter Feldherr aller Zeiten" (greatest military commander of all time), i.e.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The new order of the German Democratic Republic in the east brought about a conscious denazification, but also a repudiation of earlier turns of phrase in favour of neologisms such as *Stasi* for *Staatssicherheit* ("state security", the secret police) and *VoPo* for *Volkspolizei*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The phrase *politisches Büro*, which may be rendered literally as "office of politics" or idiomatically as "political party steering committee", became *Politbüro*.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are not only used in politics, however.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are very common in Russian, Belarusian and Ukrainian.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] They are often used as names of organizations.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Historically, popularization of abbreviations was a way to simplify mass-education in 1920s (see Likbez).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The word *kolkhoz* (*kollektívnoye khozyáystvo*, collective farm) is another example.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Leninist organisations such as the *Comintern* (*Communist International*) and *Komsomol* (*Kommunisticheskii Soyuz Molodyozhi*, or "Communist youth union") used Russian language syllabic abbreviations.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In the modern Russian language, words like *Rosselkhozbank* (from Rossiysky selskokhozyaystvenny bank — Russian Agricultural Bank, RusAg) and *Minobrnauki* (from Ministerstvo obrazovaniya i nauki — Ministry of Education and Science) are still commonly used.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] In nearby Belarus, there are *Beltelecom* (Belarus Telecommunication) and Belsat (Belarus Satellite).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Syllabic abbreviations are common in Spanish; examples abound in organization names such as Pemex for *Petróleos Mexicanos* ("Mexican Petroleums") or Fonafifo for *Fondo Nacional de Financimiento Forestal* (National Forestry Financing Fund).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] ("Banamex"), Teléfonos de México, S.A.B. de C.V.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] ("TELMEX"), Operadora de Cinemas, S.A. de C.V.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Malaysian abbreviation often uses letters from each word, while Indonesia usually uses syllables; although some cases do not follow the style.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For example, general elections in Malaysian Malay often shortened into PRU (**p**ilihan **r**aya **u**mum) while Indonesian often shortened into pemilu (**pemil**ihan **u**mum).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Another example is Ministry of Health in which Malaysian Malay uses KKM (**K**ementerian **K**esihatan **M**alaysia), compared to Indonesian Kemenkes (**Kemen**terian **Kes**ehatan).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] East Asian languages whose writing systems use Chinese characters form abbreviations similarly by using key Chinese characters from a term or phrase.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] For example, in Japanese the term for the United Nations, *kokusai rengō* (国際連合) is often abbreviated to *kokuren* (国連).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] (Such abbreviations are called ryakugo (略語) in Japanese; see also Japanese abbreviated and contracted words).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The syllabic abbreviation of kanji words is frequently used for universities: for instance, *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō daigaku* (東京大学, University of Tokyo) and is used similarly in Chinese: *Běidà* (北大) for *Běijīng Dàxué* (北京大学, Peking University).
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] Korean universities often follow the same conventions, such as *Hongdae* (홍대) as short for *Hongik Daehakgyo*, or Hongik University.
[src:abbreviation/abbreviation] The English phrase "Gung ho" originated as a Chinese abbreviation.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] An **acronym** is an abbreviation formed using the initial letters of a multi-word name or phrase.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often spelled with the initial letter of each word in all caps with no punctuation.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In English, the word is used in two ways.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In the narrow sense, an acronym is a sequence of letters (representing the initial letters of words in a phrase) when pronounced together as a single word, like *NASA*, *NATO*, or *laser*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In the broad sense, the term includes this kind of sequence when pronounced letter by letter (such as *GDP* or *USA*).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Sources that differentiate the two often call the former acronyms and the latter **initialisms** or **alphabetisms**.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] However, *acronym* is popularly used to refer to either concept, and both senses of the term are attributed as far back as the 1940s.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Dictionary and style-guide editors dispute whether the term *acronym* can be legitimately applied to abbreviations which are not pronounced as words, and there is no general agreement on standard acronym spacing, casing, and punctuation.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The phrase that the acronym stands for is called its *expansion*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The *meaning* of an acronym includes both its expansion and the meaning of its expansion.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The word *acronym* is formed from the Greek roots *akro-*, meaning 'height, summit, or tip', and *-nym*, 'name'.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] This neoclassical compound appears to have originated in German, with attestations for the German form *Akronym* appearing as early as 1921.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Citations in English date to a 1940 translation of a novel by the German writer Lion Feuchtwanger.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] English lexicography and style guides differ on whether *acronym* should apply only to abbreviations pronounced as ordinary words or also to letter-by-letter initialisms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some authorities accept or record the broader sense; others restrict *acronym* to word-pronounced forms and prefer *initialism* (or simply *abbreviation*) for the rest.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Among sources that acknowledge the broader sense, attitudes range from neutral recording to prescriptive criticism.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some mainstream English dictionaries from across the English-speaking world affirm a sense of *acronym* that does not require its pronunciation as a word.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] English language usage and style guides which have entries for *acronym* generally criticize the usage that refers to forms that are not pronounceable words.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In contrast, some style guides do support it, whether explicitly or implicitly.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The 1994 edition of *Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage* defends the usage on the basis of a claim that dictionaries do not make a distinction.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The BuzzFeed style guide describes CBS and PBS as "acronyms ending in S".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Most of the dictionary entries and style guide recommendations regarding the term *acronym* in the twentieth century did not explicitly acknowledge or support the expansive sense.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The Merriam–Webster's Dictionary of English Usage from 1994 is one of the earliest publications to advocate for the expansive sense, and all the major dictionary editions that include a sense of *acronym* equating it with *initialism* were first published in the twenty-first century.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* only included the exclusive sense for *acronym* and its earliest citation was from 1943.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In early December 2010, Duke University researcher Stephen Goranson published a citation for *acronym* to the American Dialect Society e-mail discussion list which refers to *PGN* being pronounced "pee-gee-enn", antedating English language usage of the word to 1940.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Linguist Ben Zimmer then mentioned this citation in his December 16, 2010 "On Language" column about acronyms in *The New York Times Magazine*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] By 2011, the publication of the 3rd edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* added the expansive sense to its entry for *acronym* and included the 1940 citation.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] As the *Oxford English Dictionary* structures the senses in order of chronological development, it now gives the "initialism" sense first.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Acronymy, like retronymy, is a linguistic process that has existed throughout history but for which there was little to no naming, conscious attention, or systematic analysis until relatively recent times.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Like retronymy, it became much more common in the twentieth century than it had formerly been.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] American Telephone and Telegraph Company → AT&T).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some well-known commercial examples dating from the 1890s through 1920s include "Nabisco" ("National Biscuit Company"), "Esso" (from "S.O.", from "Standard Oil"), and "Sunoco" ("Sun Oil Company").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Another field for the adoption of acronyms was modern warfare, with its many highly technical terms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The widespread, frequent use of acronyms across the whole range of linguistic registers is relatively new in most languages, becoming increasingly evident since the mid-twentieth century.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] As literacy spread and technology produced a constant stream of new and complex terms, abbreviations became increasingly convenient.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (*OED*) records the first printed use of the word *initialism* as occurring in 1899, but it did not come into general use until 1965, well after *acronym* had become common.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In English, acronyms *pronounced as words* may be a twentieth-century phenomenon.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Linguist David Wilton in *Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends* claims that "forming words from acronyms is a distinctly twentieth- (and now twenty-first-) century phenomenon.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] There is only one known pre-twentieth-century [English] word with an acronymic origin and it was in vogue for only a short time in 1886.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The use of Latin and Neo-Latin terms in vernaculars has been pan-European and pre-dates modern English.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The earliest example of a word derived from an acronym listed by the *OED* is "abjud" (now "abjad"), formed from the original first four letters of the Arabic alphabet in the late eighteenth century.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some acrostics pre-date this, however, such as the Restoration witticism arranging the names of some members of Charles II's Committee for Foreign Affairs to produce the "CABAL" ministry.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Acronyms are used most often to abbreviate names of organizations and long or frequently referenced terms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The armed forces and government agencies frequently employ acronyms; some well-known examples from the United States are among the "alphabet agencies" (jokingly referred to as "alphabet soup") created under the New Deal by Franklin D.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Business and industry also coin acronyms prolifically.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The rapid advance of science and technology also drives the usage, as new inventions and concepts with multiword names create a demand for shorter, more pronounceable names.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] One representative example, from the U.S.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Navy, is "COMCRUDESPAC", which stands for "commander, cruisers destroyers Pacific"; it is also seen as "ComCruDesPac".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Acronym use has been further popularized by text messaging on mobile phones with short message service (SMS), and instant messenger (IM).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] To fit messages into the 160-character SMS limit, and to save time, acronyms such as "GF" ("girlfriend"), "LOL" ("laughing out loud"), and "DL" ("download" or "down low") have become popular.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some prescriptivists disdain texting acronyms and abbreviations as decreasing clarity, or as failure to use "pure" or "proper" English.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Others point out that languages have always continually changed, and argue that acronyms should be embraced as inevitable, or as innovation that adapts the language to changing circumstances.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In this view, the modern practice is just the "proper" English of the current generation of speakers, much like the earlier abbreviation of corporation names on ticker tape or newspapers.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Exact pronunciation of "word acronyms" (those pronounced as words rather than sounded out as individual letters) often vary by speaker population.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] These may be regional, occupational, or generational differences, or simply personal preference.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For instance, there have been decades of online debate about how to pronounce GIF (/ɡɪf/ or /dʒɪf/) and BIOS (/ˈbaɪoʊs/, /ˈbaɪoʊz/, or /ˈbaɪɒs/).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Pronunciation may even vary within a single speaker's vocabulary, depending on narrow contexts.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] As an example, the database programming language SQL is usually said as three letters, but in reference to Microsoft's implementation is traditionally pronounced like the word *sequel*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In writing for a broad audience, the words of an acronym are typically written out in full at its first occurrence within a given text.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use (EAFU) benefits readers unfamiliar with the acronym.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Another text aid is an abbreviation key which lists and expands all acronyms used, a reference for readers who skipped past the first use.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] (This is especially important for paper media, where no search utility is available to find the first use.) It also gives students a convenient review list to memorize the important acronyms introduced in a textbook chapter.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use and abbreviation keys originated in the print era, but they are equally useful for electronic text.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] While acronyms provide convenience and succinctness for specialists, they often degenerate into confusing jargon.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] This may be intentional, to exclude readers without domain-specific knowledge.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] New acronyms may also confuse when they coincide with an already existing acronym having a different meaning.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Medical literature has been struggling to control the proliferation of acronyms, including efforts by the American Academy of Dermatology.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often taught as mnemonic devices: for example the colors of the rainbow are ROY G.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] BIV (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] They are also used as mental checklists: in aviation GUMPS stands for gas-undercarriage-mixture-propeller-seat belts.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Other mnemonic acronyms include HOMES (for the North American Great Lakes) in geography, PAVPANIC in English grammar, and PEMDAS/BODMAS in mathematics.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] It is not uncommon for acronyms to be cited in a kind of false etymology, called a folk etymology, for a word.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Such etymologies persist in popular culture but have no factual basis in historical linguistics, and are examples of language-related urban legends.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, "cop" is commonly cited as being derived, it is presumed, from "constable on patrol", and "posh" from "port outward, starboard home".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] With some of these specious expansions, the "belief" that the etymology is acronymic has clearly been tongue-in-cheek among many citers, as with "gentlemen only, ladies forbidden" for "golf", although many other (more credulous) people have uncritically taken it for fact.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Taboo words in particular commonly have such false etymologies: "shit" from "ship/store high in transit" or "special high-intensity training" and "fuck" from "for unlawful carnal knowledge", or "fornication under consent/command of the king".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In English, abbreviations have previously been marked by a wide variety of punctuation.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Obsolete forms include using an overbar or colon to show the ellipsis of letters following the initial part.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The forward slash is still common in many dialects for some fixed expressions—such as in *w/* for "with" or *A/C* for "air conditioning"—while only infrequently being used to abbreviate new terms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The apostrophe is common for grammatical contractions (e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] *don't*, *y'all*, and *ain't*) and for contractions marking unusual pronunciations (e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] *a'ight*, *cap'n*, and *fo'c'sle* for "all right", "captain", and "forecastle").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] By the early twentieth century, it was standard to use a full stop/period/point, especially in the cases of initialisms and acronyms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Previously, especially for Latin abbreviations, this was done with a full space between every full word (e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] This even included punctuation after both Roman and Arabic numerals to indicate their use in place of the full names of each number (e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Both conventions have fallen out of common use in all dialects of English, except in places where an Arabic decimal includes a medial decimal point.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Particularly in British and Commonwealth English, all such punctuation marking acronyms and other capitalized abbreviations is now uncommon and considered either unnecessary or incorrect.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The presence of all-capital letters is now thought sufficient to indicate the nature of the *UK*, the *EU*, and the *UN*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Forms such as *the U.S.A.* for "the United States of America" are now considered to indicate American or North American English.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Even within those dialects, such punctuation is becoming increasingly uncommon.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some style guides, such as that of the BBC, no longer require punctuation to show ellipsis; some even proscribe it.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Nevertheless, some influential style guides, many of them American, still require periods in certain instances.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* recommends following each segment with a period when the letters are pronounced individually, as in "K.G.B.", but not when pronounced as a word, as in "NATO".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the punctuation scheme.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] When a multiple-letter abbreviation is formed from a single word, periods are in general not used, although they may be common in informal usage.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] "TV", for example, may stand for a *single* word ("television", for instance), and is in general spelled without punctuation (except in the plural).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Although "PS" stands for the single English word "postscript" or the Latin *postscriptum*, it is often spelled with periods ("P.S.") as if parsed as Latin *post scriptum* instead.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The slash ('/', or *solidus*) is sometimes used to separate the letters in an acronym, as in "N/A" ("not applicable, not available") and "c/o" ("care of").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Inconveniently long words used frequently in related contexts can be represented according to their letter count as a numeronym.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, "i18n" abbreviates "internationalization", a computer-science term for adapting software for worldwide use; the "18" represents the 18 letters that come between the first and the last in "internationalization".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Similarly, "localization" can be abbreviated "l10n"; "multilingualization" "m17n"; and "accessibility" "a11y".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In addition to the use of a specific number replacing that many letters, the more general "x" can be used to replace an unspecified number of letters.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Examples include "Crxn" for "crystallization" and the series familiar to physicians for history, diagnosis, and treatment ("hx", "dx", "tx").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Terms relating to a command structure may also sometimes use this formatting, for example gold, silver, and bronze levels of command in UK policing being referred to as Gx, Sx, and Bx.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] There is a question about how to pluralize acronyms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Often a writer will add an 's' following an apostrophe, as in "PC's".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Turabian's *A Manual for Writers of Research Papers, Theses, and Dissertations*, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Turabian would therefore prefer "DVDs" and "URLs" but not "Ph.D.s".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Possessive plurals that also include apostrophes for mere pluralization and periods appear especially complex: for example, "the C.D.'s' labels" (the labels of the compact discs).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In some instances, however, an apostrophe may increase clarity: for example, if the final letter of an abbreviation is "S", as in "SOS's" (although abbreviations ending with S can also take "-es", e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] "SOSes"), or when pluralizing an abbreviation that has periods.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] A particularly rich source of options arises when the plural of an acronym would normally be indicated in a word other than the final word if spelled out in full.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] A classic example is "Member of Parliament", which in plural is "Members of Parliament".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] It is possible then to abbreviate this as "M's P", which was fairly common in mid-twentieth-century Australian news writing (or similar), and used by former Australian Prime Minister Ben Chifley.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] This usage is less common than forms with "s" at the end, such as "MPs", and may appear dated or pedantic.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In common usage, therefore, "weapons of mass destruction" becomes "WMDs", "prisoners of war" becomes "POWs", and "runs batted in" becomes "RBIs".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Abbreviations that come from single, rather than multiple, words—such as "TV" ("television")—are usually pluralized without apostrophes ("two TVs"); most writers feel that the apostrophe should be reserved for the possessive ("the TV's antenna").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In some languages, the convention of doubling the letters in the acronym is used to indicate plural words: for example, the Spanish *EE.UU.*, for *Estados Unidos* ('United States').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] This old convention is still sometimes followed for a limited number of English abbreviations, such as *SS.* for *Saints*, *pp.* for the plural of 'pages', or *mss.* for *manuscripts*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The most common capitalization scheme seen with acronyms is all-uppercase (all caps).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Small caps are sometimes used to make the run of capital letters seem less jarring to the reader.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, the style of some American publications, including the *Atlantic Monthly* and *USA Today*, is to use small caps for acronyms longer than three letters; thus "U.S." and "FDR" are set in normal caps, but "nato" is set in small caps.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The acronyms "AD" and "BC" are often smallcapped as well, as in: "From 4004 bc to ad 525".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Where an acronym has linguistically taken on an identity as regular word, the acronym may use normal case rules, e.g. it would appear generally in lower case, but with an initial capital when starting a sentence or when in a title.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Once knowledge of the words underlying such an acronym has faded from common recall, the acronym may be termed an **anacronym**.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Examples of anacronyms are the words "scuba", "radar", and "laser".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The word "an*acro*nym" should not be confused with the word "an*achro*nym", which is a type of misnomer.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Words derived from an acronym by affixing are typically expressed in mixed case, so the root acronym is clear.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, "pre-WWII politics", "post-NATO world", "DNase".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] In some cases a derived acronym may also be expressed in mixed case.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, "messenger RNA" and "transfer RNA" become "mRNA" and "tRNA".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some publications choose to capitalize only the first letter of acronyms, reserving all-caps styling for initialisms, writing the pronounced acronyms "Nato" and "Aids" in mixed case, but the initialisms "USA" and "FBI" in all caps.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, this is the style used in *The Guardian*, and *BBC News* typically edits to this style (though its official style guide, dating from 2003, still recommends all-caps).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the capitalization scheme.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] However, it conflicts with conventional English usage of first-letter upper-casing as a marker of proper names in many cases.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] For example, *AIDS* stands for *acquired immunodeficiency syndrome*, which is not a proper name, while *Aids* is in the style of one.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Some style manuals also base the letters' case on their number.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] While abbreviations typically exclude the initials of short function words (such as "and", "or", "of", or "to"), this is not always the case.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Sometimes function words are included to make a pronounceable acronym, such as CORE (Congress of Racial Equality).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Sometimes the letters representing these words are written in lower case, such as in the cases of "TfL" ("Transport for London") and *LotR* (*The Lord of the Rings*); this usually occurs when the acronym represents a multi-word proper noun.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Numbers (both cardinal and ordinal) in names are often represented by digits rather than initial letters, as in "4GL" ("fourth generation language") or "G77" ("Group of 77").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Large numbers may use metric prefixes, as with "Y2K" for "Year 2000".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Exceptions using initials for numbers include "TLA" ("three-letter acronym/abbreviation") and "GoF" ("Gang of Four").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Authors of expository writing will sometimes capitalize or otherwise distinctively format the initials of the expansion for pedagogical emphasis (for example, writing: "the onset of Congestive Heart Failure (CHF)" or "the onset of **c**ongestive **h**eart **f**ailure (CHF)").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p01] Capitalization like this, however, conflicts with the convention of English orthography, which generally reserves capitals in the middle of sentences for proper nouns; when following the AMA Manual of Style, this would instead be rendered as "the onset of congestive heart failure (CHF)".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some apparent acronyms or other abbreviations do not stand for anything and cannot be expanded to some meaning.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Such pseudo-acronyms may be pronunciation-based, such as "BBQ" (*bee-bee-cue*), for "barbecue", and "K9" (*kay-nine*) for "canine".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms also frequently develop as "orphan initialisms": an existing acronym is redefined as a non-acronymous name, severing its link to its previous meaning.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] For example, the letters of the "SAT", a US college entrance test originally dubbed "Scholastic Aptitude Test", no longer officially stand for anything.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] This is common with companies that want to retain brand recognition while moving away from an outdated image: American Telephone and Telegraph became AT&T and British Petroleum became BP.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] *Russia Today* has rebranded itself as *RT*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] American Movie Classics has simply rebranded itself as AMC.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Genzyme Transgenics Corporation became GTC Biotherapeutics, Inc.; The Learning Channel became TLC; MTV dropped the name Music Television out of its brand; and American District Telegraph became simply known as ADT.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] "Kentucky Fried Chicken" went partway, re-branding itself with its initialism "KFC" to de-emphasize the role of frying in the preparation of its signature dishes, though they have since returned to using both interchangeably.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The East Coast Hockey League became the ECHL when it expanded to include cities in the western United States prior to the 2003–2004 season.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms may have advantages in international markets: for example, some national affiliates of International Business Machines are legally incorporated with "IBM" in their names (for example, IBM Canada) to avoid translating the full name into local languages.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Likewise, UBS is the name of the merged Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corporation, and HSBC has replaced the long name Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The India-based JSW Group of companies is another example of the original name (Jindal South West Group) being re-branded into a pseudo-acronym while expanding into other geographical areas in and outside of India.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Rebranding can lead to redundant acronym syndrome, as when Trustee Savings Bank became TSB Bank, or when Railway Express Agency became REA Express.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] A few high-tech companies have taken the redundant acronym to the extreme: for example, ISM Information Systems Management Corp. and SHL Systemhouse Ltd.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Examples in entertainment include the television shows *CSI: Crime Scene Investigation* and *Navy: NCIS* ("Navy" was dropped in the second season), where the redundancy was likely designed to educate new viewers as to what the initials stood for.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In some cases, while the initials in an acronym may stay the same, for what those letters stand may change.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] A *backronym* (or *bacronym*) is a phrase that is constructed "after the fact" from a previously existing word.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] For example, the novelist and critic Anthony Burgess once proposed that the word "book" ought to stand for "box of organized knowledge".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] A classic real-world example of this is the name of the predecessor to the Apple Macintosh, the Apple Lisa, which was said to refer to "Local Integrated Software Architecture", but was actually named after Steve Jobs' daughter, born in 1978.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms are deliberately designed to be apt for the thing being named (by having a dual meaning or by borrowing the positive connotations of an existing word).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some examples of contrived acronyms are *USA PATRIOT*, *CAN SPAM*, *CAPTCHA*, *DOGE* and *ACT UP*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The clothing company French Connection began referring to itself as *fcuk*, standing for "French Connection United Kingdom".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The company then created T-shirts and several advertising campaigns that exploit the acronym's similarity to the taboo word "fuck".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms find frequent use as names of fictional agencies, with a famous example being frequent James Bond antagonist organization SPECTRE (Special Executive for Counterintelligence, Terrorism, Revenge and Extortion).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Department of Defense's Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) is known for developing contrived acronyms to name projects, including *RESURRECT*, *NIRVANA*, and *DUDE*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The short-form names of clinical trials and other scientific studies constitute a large class of acronyms that includes many contrived examples, as well as many with a partial rather than complete correspondence of letters to expansion components.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Examples widely known in medicine include the ALLHAT trial (Antihypertensive and Lipid-Lowering Treatment to Prevent Heart Attack Trial) and the CHARM trial (Candesartan in Heart Failure: Assessment of Reduction in Mortality and Morbidity).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] However, the purpose of clinical trial acronyms, as with gene and protein symbols, is simply to have a syntactically usable and easily recalled short name to complement the long name that is often syntactically unusable and not memorized.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] It is useful for the short name to give a reminder of the long name, which supports the reasonable censure of "cutesy" examples that provide little to no hint of it.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] But beyond that reasonably close correspondence, the short name's chief utility is in functioning cognitively as a name, rather than being a cryptic and forgettable string, albeit faithful to the matching of letters.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] At least one study has evaluated the citation impact and other traits of acronym-named trials compared with others, finding both good aspects (mnemonic help, name recall) and potential flaws (connotatively driven bias).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are chosen deliberately to avoid a name considered undesirable: For example, *Verliebt in Berlin* (*ViB*), a German telenovela, was first intended to be *Alles nur aus Liebe* ('All for Love'), but was changed to avoid the resultant acronym *ANAL*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Computer Literacy and Internet Technology qualification is known as *CLaIT*, rather than *CLIT*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In Canada, the Canadian Conservative Reform Alliance (Party) was quickly renamed to the "Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance" when its opponents pointed out that its initials spelled CCRAP (pronounced "see crap").
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Two Irish institutes of technology (Galway and Tralee) chose different acronyms from other institutes when they were upgraded from regional technical colleges.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Tralee RTC became the Institute of Technology Tralee (ITT), as opposed to Tralee Institute of Technology (TIT).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Galway RTC became Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology (GMIT), as opposed to Galway Institute of Technology (GIT).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The charity sports organization Team in Training is known as "TNT" and not "TIT".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Technological Institute of Textile & Sciences, however, is still known as "TITS".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] George Mason University was planning to name their law school the "Antonin Scalia School of Law" (ASSOL) in honor of the late Antonin Scalia, only to change it to the "Antonin Scalia Law School" later.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] A **macronym**, or **nested acronym**, is an acronym in which one or more letters stand for acronyms (or abbreviations) themselves.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The word "macronym" is a portmanteau of "macro-" and "acronym".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some macronyms can be multiply nested: the second-order acronym points to another one further down a hierarchy.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] VITAL, for example, which expands to "VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries" is a total of 15 words when fully expanded.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Fully expanded, "RARS" might thus become "Regional Advanced Television Infrared Observational Satellite Operational Vertical Sounder Retransmission Service", which would produce the much more unwieldy acronym "RATIOSOVSRS".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The latter are fully reducible in an attempt to "spell everything out and avoid all abbreviations", but the former are irreducible in that respect; they can be annotated with parenthetical explanations, but they cannot be eliminated from speech or writing in any useful or practical way.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The name is thus itself more symbol than acronym, and its expansion cannot replace it while preserving its function in natural syntax as a name within a clause clearly parsable by human readers or listeners.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] A special type of macronym, the recursive acronym, has letters whose expansion refers back to the macronym itself.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] One of the earliest examples appears in *The Hacker's Dictionary* as MUNG, which stands for "MUNG Until No Good".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] With English terminology, discussions of languages with syllabic or logographic writing systems (such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean), "acronyms" describe the short forms that take selected characters from a multi-character word.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] For example, in Chinese, 'university' (大學/大学, lit.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] 'great learning') is usually abbreviated simply as 大 ('great') when used with the name of the institute.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] So 'Peking University' (北京大学) is commonly shortened to 北大 (lit.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] 'north-great') by also only taking the first character of *Peking*, the "northern capital" (北京; *Beijing*).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In some cases, however, other characters than the first can be selected.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] For example, the local short form of 'Hong Kong University' (香港大學) uses *Kong* (港大) rather than *Hong*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Many aspects of academics in Korea follow similar acronym patterns as Chinese, owing to the two languages' commonalities, like using the word for 'big' or 'great' i.e.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] *dae* (대), to refer to universities (대학; *daehak*, literally 'great learning' although 'big school' is an acceptable alternate).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] They can be interpreted similarly to American university appellations, such as "UPenn" or "Texas Tech".
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are shortened forms of the school's name, like how Hongik University (홍익대학교, *Hongik Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Hongdae* (홍대, 'Hong, the big [school]' or 'Hong-U') Other acronyms can refer to the university's main subject, e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Korea National University of Education (한국교원대학교, *Hanguk Gyowon Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Gyowondae* (교원대, 'Big Ed.' or 'Ed.-U').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Other schools use a Koreanized version of their English acronym.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (한국과학기술원, *Hanguk Gwahak Gisulwon*) is referred to as KAIST (카이스트, *Kaiseuteu*) in both English and Korean.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The 3 most prestigious schools in Korea are known as SKY (스카이, *seukai*), combining the first letter of their English names (**S**eoul National, **K**orea, and **Y**onsei Universities).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In addition, the College Scholastic Ability Test (대학수학능력시험, *Daehak Suhang Neungryeok Siheom*) is shortened to *Suneung* (수능, 'S.A.').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The Japanese language makes extensive use of abbreviations, but only some of these are acronyms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Chinese-based words (Sino-Japanese vocabulary) use similar acronym formation to Chinese, like *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō Daigaku* (東京大学, *Tokyo University*).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] It is not always the case that the first character of each word is used, as in Saikyō for 埼京, from *Saitama* + *Tōkyō* (埼玉＋東京), which uses the second character of 東京.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Non-Chinese foreign borrowings (gairaigo) are instead frequently abbreviated as clipped compounds, rather than acronyms, using several initial sounds.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] This is visible in katakana transcriptions of foreign words, but is also found with native words (written in hiragana).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] For example, the *Pokémon* media franchise's name originally stood for "pocket monsters" (**ポケ**ット·**モン**スター [po-ke-tto-mon-su-tā] (arrow for r) ポケモン), which is still the long-form of the name in Japanese, or "wāpuro" for "word processor" (**ワー**ド·**プロ**セッサー [wā-do-pu-ro-se-ssā] (arrow for r) ワープロ).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] To a greater degree than English, German often uses syllabic abbreviations instead of acronyms.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some examples are *Gestapo* rather than *GSP* (for *Geheime Staatspolizei*, 'Secret State Police'); *Flak* rather than *FAK* (for *Fliegerabwehrkanone*, 'anti-aircraft gun'); and *Kripo* rather than *KP* (for *Kriminalpolizei*, 'detective division police').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The overuse of such contractions has been mockingly labeled *Aküfi* (for *Abkürzungsfimmel*, 'strange habit of abbreviating').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Examples of *Aküfi* include *Vokuhila* (for *vorne kurz, hinten lang*, 'short in the front, long in the back', i.e., a mullet haircut) and the mocking of Adolf Hitler's title as *Gröfaz* (*Größter Feldherr aller Zeiten*, 'Greatest General of all Time').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Examples (keeping in mind that Hebrew reads right-to-left): ארה״ב (for ארצות הברית, the United States); ברה״מ (for ברית המועצות, the Soviet Union); ראשל״צ (for ראשון לציון, Rishon LeZion); ביה״ס (for בית הספר, the school).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] An example that takes only the initial letters from its component words is צה״ל (*Tzahal*, for צבא הגנה לישראל, Israel Defense Forces).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In inflected forms, the abbreviation sign *gershayim* remains between the second-last and last letters of the non-inflected form of the acronym (e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] 'report', singular: דו״ח, plural: דו״חות; 'squad commander', masculine: מ״כ, feminine: מ״כית).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] There is also a widespread use of acronyms in Indonesia in every aspect of social life.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are considered formal (or officially adopted), while many more are considered informal, slang, or colloquial.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The capital's metropolitan area (Jakarta and its surrounding satellite regions), *Jabodetabek*, is another acronym.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] This stands for *Jakarta-Bogor-Depok-Tangerang-Bekasi*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Many highways are also named by the acronym method, e.g.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] *Jalan Tol* ('Toll Road'), *Jagorawi* (*Jakarta-Bogor-Ciawi*), *Purbaleunyi* (*Purwakarta-Bandung-Cileunyi*), and *Joglo Semar* (*Jogja-Solo-Semarang*).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In some languages, especially those that use certain alphabets, many acronyms come from the governmental use, particularly in the military and law enforcement services.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The Indonesian military (TNI – *Tentara Nasional Indonesia*) and Indonesian police (POLRI – *Kepolisian Republik Indonesia*) are known for heavy acronyms use.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Although not as common as in its sister language Indonesian, a number of Malaysian (*Bahasa Malaysia*) words are formed by merging two words, such as *tadika* from *taman didikan kanak-kanak* ('kindergarten') and *pawagam* from *panggung wayang gambar*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] This, however, has been less prevalent in the modern era, in contrary to Indonesian.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] It is still often for names such as organisation names, among the most famous being MARA from *Majlis Amanah Rakyat* ('People's Trust Council'), a government agency in Malaysia.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Rules in writing initialisms in Malaysian differ based on its script.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In its Latin form, the initialism would be spelt much like in English, using capitals written without any spacing, such as TNB for *Tenaga Nasional Berhad*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In Jawi, however, initialisms differ depending on the source language.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] For Malay initialisms, the initial Jawi letters would be written separated by a period such as د.ب.ڤ for ديوان بهاس دان ڤوستاک.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] If the initialism is from a different language, however, it would be written by transliterating each letter from the original language, such as عيم.سي.عيم.سي. for MCMC, or الفا.ڤي.ثيتا for Α.Π.Θ.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Acronyms that use parts of words (not necessarily syllables) are commonplace in Russian as well, e.g. Газпром (*Gazprom*), for Газовая промышленность (*Gazovaya promyshlennost*, 'gas industry').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Most commonly they are pronounced as words, unless they lack vowels, in which case they are pronounced by letters e.g. ФСБ (*ef-es-beh*, 'FSB'), США (*seh-sheh-ah*, USA).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Some foreigh acronyms became own words, such as айти (*IT*) and пиар (*PR*).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Historically, *OTMA* was an acronym sometimes used by the daughters of Emperor Nicholas II of Russia and his consort, Alexandra Feodorovna, as a group nickname for themselves, built from the first letter of each girl's name in the order of their births: Olga, Tatiana, Maria, and Anastasia.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In Swahili, acronyms are common for naming organizations such as *TUKI*, which stands for *Taasisi ya Uchunguzi wa Kiswahili* ('Institute for Swahili Research').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Multiple initial letters (often the initial syllable of words) are often drawn together, as seen more in some languages than others.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In Vietnamese, which has an abundance of compound words, initialisms are very commonly used for both proper and common nouns.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Longer examples include *CHXHCNVN* (*Cộng hòa Xã hội chủ nghĩa Việt Nam*, 'Socialist Republic of Vietnam') and *MTDTGPMNVN* (*Mặt trận Dân tộc Giải phóng miền Nam Việt Nam*, 'Liberation Army of South Vietnam or the National Liberation Front of South Vietnam').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Long initialisms have become widespread in legal contexts in Vietnam, for example *TTLT-VKSNDTC-TANDTC*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] It is also common for a writer to coin an ad hoc initialism for repeated use in an article.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Each letter in an initialism corresponds to one morpheme, that is, one syllable.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] When the first letter of a syllable has a tone mark or other diacritic, the diacritic may be omitted from the initialism, for example *ĐNA* or *ĐNÁ* for *Đông Nam Á* ('Southeast Asia') and *LMCA* or *LMCÂ* for *Liên minh châu Âu* ('European Union').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The letter *Ư* is often replaced by *W* in initialisms to avoid confusion with *U*, for example *UBTWMTTQVN* or *UBTƯMTTQVN* for *Ủy ban Trung ương Mặt trận Tổ quốc Việt Nam* ('Central Committee of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Initialisms are purely a written convenience, being pronounced the same way as their expansions.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] As the names of many Vietnamese letters are disyllabic, it would be less convenient to pronounce an initialism by its individual letters.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Acronyms pronounced as words are rare in Vietnamese, occurring when an acronym itself is borrowed from another language.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Examples include *SIĐA* (pronounced [s̪i˧ ˀɗaː˧]), a respelling of the French acronym *SIDA* ('AIDS'); *VOA* (pronounced [vwaː˧]), a literal reading of the English initialism for 'Voice of America'; and *NASA* (pronounced [naː˧ zaː˧]), borrowed directly from the English acronym.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] As in Chinese, many compound words can be shortened to the first syllable when forming a longer word.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] For example, the term *Việt Cộng* is derived from the first syllables of *Việt Nam* ('Vietnam') and *Cộng sản* ('communist').
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] This mechanism is limited to Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Unlike with Chinese, such clipped compounds are considered to be portmanteau words or blend words rather than acronyms or initialisms, because the Vietnamese alphabet still requires each component word to be written as more than one character.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In languages where nouns are declined, various methods are used.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] The process above is similar to the way that hyphens are used for clarity in English when prefixes are added to acronyms: thus *pre-NATO policy* (rather than *preNATO*).
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In languages such as Scottish Gaelic and Irish, where lenition (initial consonant mutation) is commonplace, acronyms must also be modified in situations where case and context dictate it.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] In the case of Scottish Gaelic, a lower-case *h* is often added after the initial consonant; for example, 'BBC Scotland' in the genitive case would be written as *BhBC Alba*, with the acronym pronounced *VBC*.
[src:abbreviation/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Gaelic acronym for *telebhisean* 'television' is *TBh*, pronounced *TV*, as in English.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He was the younger brother of Puma founder Rudolf Dassler.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The brothers were partners in a shoe company Adolf started, Gebrüder Dassler Schuhfabrik ("Dassler Brothers Shoe Factory").
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] However, after a feud developed between them following World War II, the brothers went separate ways and started their respective companies in 1948.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Dassler was an innovator in sports shoe design and one of the early promoters who obtained endorsements from athletes to drive sales of his products.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] From his concepts, he created Adidas, which had 17 factories and annual sales of one billion Deutschmarks at the time of his death.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi supported himself while attempting to start up his business by repairing shoes in town.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Dassler became quite adept at modifying available devices to help mechanize production in the absence of electricity.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Using belts, for example, he rigged a leather milling machine to a mounted, stationary bicycle powered by the firm's first employee.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The business was driven by Adi's vision of specialized sport designs.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He produced one of the earliest spiked shoes, with spikes forged by the smithy of the family of his friend Fritz Zehlein.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He constantly experimented with various materials, such as shark skin and kangaroo leather, to create strong but lightweight shoes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Years later his widow, Käthe Dassler, said: "Developing shoes was his hobby, not his job.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] After the war, Rudolf wanted to become a policeman.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] But after he completed his training, he joined Adi's firm on 1 July 1923.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] By 1925, the Dasslers were making leather *Fußballschuhe* (football boots) with nailed studs and track shoes with hand-forged spikes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Two factors paved the way for the transformation of the business from a small regional factory, which they moved to in 1927 from their parents' home, to the international shoe distributor it would become.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] First was the interest showed by former Olympian and then coach of the German Olympic track-and-field team, Josef Waitzer.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] On learning of the plant and Adi's experiments, Waitzer travelled from Munich to Herzogenaurach to see for himself.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] A long friendship developed between the two, based on interest in improving athletic performance with improved footwear, and Waitzer became something of a consultant to the company.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The relationship proved extremely valuable in giving Adi access to the athletes, both German and foreign, at the 1936 Berlin Olympics.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] As early as the 1928 Amsterdam Games, the Dasslers' footwear was being used in international competitions.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Lina Radke, for example, the German middle distance runner who won gold in 1928, wore Dassler track shoes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Likewise, a German gold medal runner wore Dassler shoes at the 1932 Los Angeles games.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The second key factor for the shoe firm in the early 1930s was the role sport played in Adolf Hitler's racial-nationalist philosophy.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] With the rise of the Nazi Party, athletic teamwork was prioritized.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The Dassler brothers did not fail to see how their economic interests would benefit from politics and joined the Nazi Party on 1 May 1933, three months after Hitler became Chancellor.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf was said to be the most ardent believer of the three.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In 1935, Adi decided that becoming a coach of and supplier to clubs affiliated with the Hitler Youth was essential to expanded production.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] During his denazification proceedings after the war, Adi pointed out that he had confined himself to coaching and avoided political rallies.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He testified that he was involved in clubs with other political affiliations, such as a liberal gymnastic club, Herzogenaurach's conservative KHC football club and a workers' sports club named "The Union".
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In the early 1930s, Adi enrolled in the *Schuhfachschule* (the Footwear Technical College) in Pirmasens.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] One of the instructors was Franz Martz, a master producer of lasts.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Dassler became a frequent house guest of Martz, who allowed him to begin a relationship with his fifteen-year-old daughter Käthe.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Unlike Rudolf's wife Friedl (née Strasser), Käthe was somewhat self-assertive and suspicious of the brusque ways of Franconians.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] She had frequent run-ins with Adi's parents as well as Rudolf and his wife, all of whom lived in the same house.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Years later, in a letter to Puma's American distributor, Rudolf blamed the rift with his brother entirely on Käthe, claiming that she "tried to interfere in business matters".
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He claimed that the brothers' relations were "ideal" until 1933.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Käthe gave birth to their son Horst in March 1936, their first daughter Inge in June 1938, and their second daughter Karin in 1941.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] After the war, two more daughters were born, Brigit in May 1946 and Sigrid in 1953.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi saw the Berlin Olympics as the key springboard for international exposure.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Although his relation with Waitzer ensured that most German athletes wore Dassler footwear, he had another athlete principally in mind, American track and field star Jesse Owens.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi's association with Owens proved crucial to the success of the Dassler brothers' firm and immediately catapulted it into an international competitor in sportswear.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] When American GIs discovered that the Dassler factory was where the shoes for Owens' Olympic victories were made, they decided to let the works remain.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Once war began, the Dasslers' ability to profit from Nazi enthusiasm for sport ended as the Reich became a war machine.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The Dassler firm was permitted to operate, but its production was severely curtailed.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] On 7 August 1940, Adi received notice of his conscription into the Wehrmacht.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Although he reported in December to begin training as a radio technician, he was relieved of duty on 28 February 1941 and sent back to continue running the shoe factory.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In the early years of the war, the firm was partially converted to a factory for the production of military material.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Staff were reduced and supply was hard to come by.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] It continued to produce Waitzer shoes, although some of its football line became known as "Kampf" and "Blitz".
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] By October 1942, worker shortages became so severe that Adi requested the use of five Soviet prisoners of war to man his production line.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Wartime conditions exacerbated the simmering dispute between Rudolf's and Adi's families.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The house that Christoph, Pauline, sons Rudolf and Adi and their wives, and five grandchildren all lived in together seemed stifling, and forced family association at work was further complicated by the brothers' sister Marie's employment there.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf, angry that Adi aimed to be the leader of the Dassler firm and therefore released from the Wehrmacht, began to assert himself among family members.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The decision devastated his sister, since those not employed in permitted industries were nearly guaranteed to be drafted as the army's manpower needs increased.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Marie's sons were eventually conscripted and never returned.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Fritz Dassler, who was not on speaking terms with Adi, made a similar decision, laying off a teenaged seamstress who worked for his lederhosen manufacturer, but had worked previously for four years for Adi, who managed to provide her a job at the shoe factory for the rest of the war.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf, who had already served four years during the Great War, saw his rage boil over when he was called up again in January 1943 as part of a total mobilization program.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He later expressed to the Puma American distributors the belief that he was unfairly repaid for getting his brother "released for the factory" in 1942, and claimed that for his own immediate conscription he "had to thank my brother and his [Nazi] party friends …".
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Six months later, the factory was shut down but as part of the Reich's *Totaler Krieg—Kürzester Krieg* (Total War—Shortest War) campaign, part of which involved converting all industry to military production.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] On leave at the time of the shutdown, Rudolf intended to take some of the leather inventory for his own later use.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In December 1943, the Dassler firm had their equipment replaced by spot-welding machines designed to make Panzerschrecks instead of shoes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] These anti-tank weapons were originally made at the Schriker & Co. plant in nearby Vach, which shifted assembly to Herzogenaurach to avoid Allied air raids.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Back in Poland, Rudolf continued to make good on his resolve to wrest the plant from his brother.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Using contacts at the *Luftwaffe*, he attempted to have the production of Panzerschrecks replaced by government-ordered production of army boots under a patent he personally held.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The patent proved defective and his plan came to nothing.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Unable to obtain permission to leave his outpost, Rudolf turned to his own devising.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Several weeks before 19 January 1945, the Soviets overran Tuschin (which then reverted to its original name, Tuszyn) and decimated his unit.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf fled to Herzogenaurach, where a doctor provided him a certificate of military incapacity owing to a frozen foot.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The sources for what Rudolf did between his desertion from Tuschin is among records disputed in American denazification panels.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] On the day after his and Adi's father Christoph Dassler's funeral on 4 April 1945, Rudolf was arrested and taken to the Bärenschanze prison run by the Gestapo in Nürnberg.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He remained there until the Allied liberation in early May.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] When American troops reached Herzogenaurach, tanks paused before the Dassler factory, pondering whether to blow it up.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Käthe immediately approached the troops and argued that the plant was simply a sports shoe producer.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The troops spared the plant, taking over the family house in the process.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Two weeks after the liberation of Herzogenaurach, Rudolf returned.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] As denazification proceeded, the threat of liability from their Nazi past drove an irreconcilable rift between brothers Rudolf and Adi, each seeking to save himself.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He was sent to an internment camp in Hammelburg.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf began to prepare a defense in which he asserted that he did not voluntarily help the Reich and did not engage in SS or SD activities.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The American investigators soon discovered his early Nazi party membership and proof that he had volunteered for the Wehrmacht in 1941.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf's key problem was explaining his activities after he had been summoned to Nuremberg in March by the Gestapo.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf maintained that he had been summoned on 13 March for an investigation of his earlier unauthorized departure from Tuschin, and did nothing but report daily to the Gestapo while they investigated him for over two weeks.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He claimed that he had escaped on 20 March.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf used written statements of his former superior in Tuschin, who was in the same camp and alleged to be the intelligence chief of the region, and a driver he had encountered after he was arrested by the Gestapo in April, who was incarcerated with Rudolf.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf made much use of the latter's testimony, and averred that he had been sentenced by the Gestapo to Dachau concentration camp.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf claimed that the driver, who had been ordered to shoot all the prisoners en route, disregarded the order and continued toward Dachau, but was stopped by advancing Allied troops, to whom he released the prisoners, including Rudolf.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The American investigator in charge of the case did not credit any of this testimony, which he regarded as mere cover for the unlawful activities of all three men.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He noted that both Rudolf's wife and his brother Adi testified that Rudolf had worked for the Gestapo.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The investigation continued for nearly a year.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] During that time, it became apparent that it was not possible to hold all the prisoners for a detailed examination of the case.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The authorities decided to release all persons not deemed to be a security threat.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Before Rudolf was released, Adi had to appear before the denazification panel.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The result was announced on 13 July 1946: Adi was declared a *Belasteter*, the second most serious category of Nazi offenders, which included profiteers, and could lead to a sentence of up to 10 years in prison for those convicted.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The immediate threat was that he would be removed from management of the firm.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] His early membership in the Nazi Party and the Hitler Youth were not contestable.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] On appeal, he amassed a portfolio of testimony attesting to his good conduct during the war.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi's staunchest supporter was Herzogenaurach's mayor, who the Allied forces trusted.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] A nearby mayor, who was half-Jewish, testified that Adi warned him of a potential Gestapo arrest, and hid him on his own property.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] A longtime Communist party member testified that Adi was never involved in political activities.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi showed that, far from profiting from the forced weapons production, the firm lost 100,000 marks.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Despite Adi's evidence, the committee did not acquit him.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Instead, they reclassified him as *Minderbelasteter* (Lesser Offender), a category of lesser culpability resulting in probation of two to three years with various conditions but still requiring that Adi not operate Dassler Shoes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi hired counsel to appeal the decision.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf, who had just been released, saw this as his opportunity to wrest control of the business from Adi.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In the course of the appeal proceedings, Rudolf Dassler inserted statements that claimed that Adi Dassler had organized the production of weapons himself and for his own profit and that Rudolf would have resisted the change in production if he were present.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He claimed that his brother had falsely denounced him and that Adi had made political speeches to employees at the plant.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Among other proofs submitted by Adi's counsel was a strong denial of all Rudolf's claims by Käthe.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] On 11 November 1946 the Spruchkammer Höchstadt sitting in Herzogenaurach changed Adi's status to *Mitläufer* (follower), relieving him of most of his civil disabilities, but still required some supervision.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] On 3 February 1947, ownership was returned and he was formally granted permission to resume management of the firm.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf's belief that Adi had denounced him and his conduct during his brother's appeal made further relations between them impossible.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In fact, it irreparably divided the family.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Mother Paulina sided with Rudolf and Friedl, who cared for her the rest of her life.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Their sister Marie, who never forgave Rudolf for the death of her sons, sided with Adi and Käthe.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Rudolf, his wife and two children left the family home and moved across the river, where he took over the second factory of the Dassler firm.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In their separation Adi retained the first factory and the family villa.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] As for the rest of the firm's assets, the two divided them one-by-one.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Once the brothers divided their businesses they never spoke again.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] After the war, the Dassler firm found itself with some of the same problems that it faced at the beginning.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] A world war had decimated the German economy, and supplies for the shoe factory were hard to come by.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In addition, the firm had to convert back from weapons to shoe production.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] This time, the American occupying authorities were interested in reviving economic activity, so they gave the firm active encouragement.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] American officers had commandeered the Dassler house for their residence in April 1945, so Adi had close contact with officials who gave him access to unneeded war material for production.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Until a source of leather became available, Adi made use of the rubber from fuel tanks and rafts and canvas from tents to make shoes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi was able to produce shoes, and save for the months in 1946 while under the classification of *Belasteter*.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He was able to manage the business from July 1946 to February 1947 under the supervision of a trustee, until the business separation from his brother in 1948.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] During the negotiations to separate the firm, Rudolf and Adi allowed the employees to determine which resulting firm they would work for.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Because Rudolf had mainly concerned himself with sales and administration, most of the sales staff opted to join Rudolf at the Würtzburger Strasse factory.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The rest, including almost all the technicians and those involved in product development and production, remained with Adi.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi ended up with nearly two-thirds of the employees.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] To partially fill the void left by the departure of the administrative personnel, Käthe and her sister Marianne Martz joined the firm and acted in a variety of capacities.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Meanwhile, Adi was concerned about designing a distinctive look for his shoes, at least partially so that it would be possible to show which athletes used his footwear.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He fell upon the idea of coloring the straps used for reinforcement on the sides of the shoes a different color than the shoes themselves.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He experimented with different numbers of straps and ultimately decided upon three.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The "three stripes" became a distinctive mark of Adidas shoes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In March 1949, Dassler registered the three stripe logo as the company's trademark.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] As for the company's name, the plan was to use a contraction of Adi's nickname and last name, much as Rudolf originally contemplated by naming his firm "Ruda" before deciding on "Puma", but "Addas" was rejected on the ground that it was used by a children's shoe manufacturer.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In his August 1949 company registration, Adi added a handwritten "i" between Ad- and -das to maintain the contraction (***Adi Das***sler).
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] As a result, the company became known as *Adolf Dassler adidas Schuhfabrik*.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Like the Dasslers, Sepp Herberger joined the Nazi Party in 1933.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In 1936, after Germany's humiliating quarter-final defeat by Norway at the Berlin Games, the Nazi sports authorities appointed him to coach the national football team.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Herberger began an association with the Dassler firm, having been cultivated by Rudolf Dassler.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] After the breakup, Herberger sided with the Puma firm, until Rudolf once again felt his authority challenged and insulted him.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Herberger switched his allegiance to Adidas.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Some thought it involved the payments owed if the German team wore Puma shoes.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In many respects, the fit was better with Adi, who was quiet, willing to learn the needs of football players and more innovative than his brother.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Herberger's drive to make Germany a dominant force in international football predated the war.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] He learned of 18 year old Fritz Walter in 1938 and began grooming him for the team.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] When war came, Herberger was able to keep Walter out of the army.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] After the war, Herberger was deemed a *Mitläufer* and the post-war German authorities continued him as the coach of the national team.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adi soon became a regular part of the entourage of the national team, who sat beside Herberger and adjusted players' shoes mid-game.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] West Germany, established in May 1949, was not eligible for the 1950 World Cup, the first after the war, and so all preparations were made with a view toward the 1954 matches in Switzerland.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] By that time Adidas's football boots were considerably lighter than the ones made before the war, based on English designs.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] At the World Cup Adi had a secret weapon, which he revealed when West Germany made the finals against the overwhelmingly favored Hungarian team, which was undefeated since May 1950 and had defeated West Germany 8–3 in group play.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Despite this defeat, West Germany made the knock-out rounds by twice defeating Turkey handily.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The team defeated Yugoslavia and Austria to reach the final, a remarkable achievement, where the hope of many German fans was simply that the team "avoid another humiliating defeat" at the hands of the Hungarians.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The day of the final began with light rain, which brightened the prospects of the West German team who called it "*Fritz Walter-Wetter*", because the team's best player excelled in muddy conditions.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Dassler informed Herberger before the match of his latest innovation—"screw in studs." Unlike the traditional boot which had fixed leather spike studs, Dassler's shoe allowed spikes of various lengths to be affixed depending on the state of the pitch.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The longer spikes improved the footing of West German players compared to the Hungarians, whose mud-caked boots were also much heavier.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The West Germans staged a come-from-behind upset, winning 3-2 in what became known as the Miracle of Bern.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Herberger publicly praised Dassler as a key contributor to the win.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Dassler was married to Käthe until his death from heart failure in 1978.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In 1973, their son Horst Dassler founded Arena, a producer of swimming equipment.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] After Adi's death, his son and wife took over the management of Adidas.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] Adidas was transformed into a private limited company in 1989, but remained family property until its IPO in 1995.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] The last of the family members who worked for Adidas was Frank Dassler (the grandson of Rudolf), head of the legal department since 2004, who resigned in January 2018.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] In 2006, a sculpture of Dassler was unveiled in the Adi Dassler Stadium in Herzogenaurach.
[src:abbreviation/adi-dassler] It was created by the artist Josef Tabachnyk.
[src:abbreviation/ama-manual-of-style] The manual was first published in 1962, and its current edition, the 11th, was released in 2020.
[src:abbreviation/ama-manual-of-style] It covers a range of topics for authors and editors in medicine and related health fields.
[src:abbreviation/ama-manual-of-style] The online edition also has regular updates.
[src:abbreviation/ama-manual-of-style] Style points that have changed since the last edition or new guidance such as how to present new terms like COVID-19 and SARS-CoV-2 or address race and ethnicity in science publication.
[src:abbreviation/ama-manual-of-style] AMA style is widely used, either entirely or with modifications, by many other scientific journals (including medical, nursing, and other healthcare journals), in many textbooks, and in academia (for papers written in classes).
[src:abbreviation/ama-manual-of-style] Along with APA style and CSE style, it is one of the major style regimes for such work.
[src:abbreviation/ama-manual-of-style] Many publications have small local style guides that cascade over AMA, APA, or CSE style.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] Born in the village of Drenovë, Asdreni completed his academic studies at the University of Bucharest in Romania where he enthusiastically committed himself to the Independence of Albania from the Ottoman Empire.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] He maintained close liaison with fellow Gjergj Fishta and Lasgush Poradeci and was notably inspired by the patriots Girolamo de Rada and Naim Frashëri.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] On the 30th of June 2021 the new 10000 Lekë banknote was issued by the Bank of Albania with the main portrait being that of Asdreni.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] Asdreni was born as Aleksandër Stavre Drenova on 11 April 1872 into an Albanian peasant family of Eastern Orthodox faith in the village of Drenovë close to the city of Korçë in what was then part of the Ottoman Empire and is now Albania.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] In his native village he properly received his early formal education at a Greek primary school and had just started secondary school in Korçë subsequently his father, Stavri Thimiu, died leaving him fatherless.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] The surrounding region Korçë had been a prime source of Albanian migration which was additionally strengthened by an earthquake in 1879.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] He consequently migrated to Bucharest in 1885 and rejoined his more elderly brothers where he also commenced his short-living studies at the Faculty of Political Science of the University of Bucharest.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] In the new country, Asdreni came into liaison with other Albanian intellectuals and writers with whom he started to strengthen the Albanian diaspora in Romania for the struggle of national liberation.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] Prior to that, he was strongly inspired by Girolamo de Rada and Naim Frashëri as well as by the Albanian Renaissance in which the Albanians came to acknowledge themselves as a nation deserving the right to govern themselves.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] He was initially buried there, at the Sfânta Vineri Cemetery (where Nikolla Naço is also buried), but his remains were brought to Albania and buried in Drenovë in 1974.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] The literary career of Asdreni blossomed simultaneously with the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:abbreviation/asdreni] His poem "Kënga e bashkimit" (The Song of Unity), published in the volume Ëndrra [dh]e lotë ("Dreams and tears", 1912), is a clear adaptation of the Romanian song "Hora Unirii" by Vasile Alecsandri.
